/*
====================================================================
ðŸ“˜ Introduction to STRINGS in C++
(Complete Lecture Flow â€“ No Skips)
====================================================================

We study Data Structures and Algorithms because we deal with data. Data
must be stored properly and accessed fast. So the first and most basic
question is always: what type of data do we have?

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Types of Data (Quick Revision)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
If the data is numbers like 1, 2, 3, 4, then we store it in int.
If the data is decimal values like 3.14 or 9.81, we use float or double.
If the data represents true or false, we use bool.
If the data is a single alphabet like A, B, C, then we use char.

So far, all data types work perfectly for their respective use cases.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Real-World Problem: Why Strings Are Needed
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Consider a real-world example such as an email ID:
rohitnegi@gmail.com

This is not an int, not a float, not a bool, and not a single char.
However, each individual character is a char. This means text is simply
multiple characters combined together. Therefore, we need a way to
store multiple characters as a single unit. This is where strings come
into the picture.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Character Array (Before String Concept)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
To store a word like APPLE, we can use a character array:

char arr[5] = {'A', 'P', 'P', 'L', 'E'};

Memory representation:
Index :  0   1   2   3   4
Value :  A   P   P   L   E

The text is stored correctly, but taking input and printing using this
method creates problems.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Problem with Input Using Character Array
--------------------------------------------------------------------
If we take input like this:

char arr[10];
for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    cin >> arr[i];
}

If the user enters fewer than 10 characters, the program still waits.
If the user enters more than 10 characters, overflow occurs. Fixed-size
arrays are therefore impractical for real-world text input.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Null Character '\0' (Most Important Concept)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
The null character '\0' has ASCII value 0 and marks the end of a string.
The programmer does not insert it manually; the system adds it
automatically.

Example input:
APPLE

Memory becomes:
Index :  0   1   2   3   4   5
Value :  A   P   P   L   E   \0

The null character tells the system where the string ends.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Why cout << arr Works
--------------------------------------------------------------------
When we write:
cout << arr;

The system starts printing from arr[0] and continues printing characters
until it encounters '\0'.

Example:
char arr[] = {'R','O','\0','H','I'};
cout << arr;

Output:
RO

Printing stops as soon as '\0' is found. Everything after it is ignored.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Why Null Character Is Needed
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Without '\0', we would need to store string length separately, which
would require extra memory and extra logic. The null character allows
automatic detection of the string end, making the process memory
efficient and faster.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Fixed Size Array Causes Memory Waste
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Example:
char arr[1000];

Input:
MEN

Only 3 bytes are needed, but 1000 bytes are reserved. The remaining
memory is wasted. Memory should be allocated only as much as required.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Solution: string (STL)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
The C++ string is a dynamic character container. It automatically
manages memory, is stored in heap memory, and is internally similar to
vector<char>.

Basic usage:
string s;
cin >> s;
cout << s;

The cin statement stops reading input at space, tab, or enter.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Problem with cin and String
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Input:
Rohit Negi

Using:
cin >> s;

Only "Rohit" is stored because cin treats space as a separator.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Solution: getline()
--------------------------------------------------------------------
To read complete text including spaces:

string s;
getline(cin, s);
cout << s;

getline reads spaces, tabs, and stops only when ENTER is pressed.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
String Size
--------------------------------------------------------------------
string s = "Rohit";
cout << s.size();

Output:
5

The null character '\0' is not counted in size().

--------------------------------------------------------------------
String Concatenation
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Using + operator:
string s1 = "Rohit";
string s2 = "Mohit";
string s3 = s1 + s2;
cout << s3;

Output:
RohitMohit

Using append():
s1.append(s2);

--------------------------------------------------------------------
push_back() and pop_back()
--------------------------------------------------------------------
string s = "Rohit";
s.push_back('P');   // RohitP
s.pop_back();       // Rohi

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Escape Character '\'
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Problematic code:
string s = "Rohit is a "good" boy";   // ERROR

The compiler thinks the string ends early.

Correct way:
string s = "Rohit is a \"good\" boy";
cout << s;

Output:
Rohit is a "good" boy

The escape character tells the compiler to treat the next character as
a normal character.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Reverse a String
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Logic:
Use two pointers, one at the start and one at the end. Swap characters
and move inward.

Code:
string s = "Rohit";
int start = 0;
int end = s.size() - 1;

while(start < end) {
    swap(s[start], s[end]);
    start++;
    end--;
}

cout << s;

Output:
tihoR

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Find Length Without Using size()
--------------------------------------------------------------------
int len = 0;
while(s[len] != '\0') {
    len++;
}
cout << len;

This works because every string internally ends with '\0'.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Palindrome Check
--------------------------------------------------------------------
string s = "naman";
int start = 0;
int end = s.size() - 1;

while(start < end) {
    if(s[start] != s[end]) {
        cout << "Not Palindrome";
        return 0;
    }
    start++;
    end--;
}

cout << "Palindrome";

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Final Summary
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Character arrays are fixed-size and require manual handling.
C++ string is dynamic, safe, and efficient.
The null character '\0' is the backbone of string handling.
getline() is used for full-line input.
Strings use heap memory and work on the same concept as vector.

====================================================================
End of Lecture Notes
====================================================================
*/
